Module MathUtils
Package mathUtils.calculus

Interface Function

Functional Interface:
This is a functional interface and can therefore be used as the assignment target for a lambda expression or method reference.
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Function
This interface represents a basic mathematical function by means of \( y=f(x) \). Various operations can be performed, like differentiation and integration. Functions are computed in an entirely numerical, non-analytical way. For a more precise way of computing differentials, integrals, etc. please make use of the Polynomial class instead, which makes calculations in an analytical way.
Since:
18.05.2020
See Also:
Polynomial

  • Method Details

    • y

      double y​(double x)
      This is the actual function. It should be overridden using lambda expression, so to give a functional and mathematical representation. For example, to express
      \( f(x) = \sin(x) \)
      write:
      Function f = x -> Math.sin(x);
      Parameters:
      x - The function's input
      Returns:
      The value of y according to the function

    • limit

      default double limit​(double c)
      Calculates the limit of this function as x approaches a certain value. It is equivalent to:

      \( \displaystyle\lim\limits_{x \to c} f(x) \)

      Note that this method simply delegates to mathUtils.calculus.MathTools.limit(double c, Function f).
      Parameters:
      c - The value x aproaches
      Returns:
      The limit as x aproaches the given value

    • derivative

      default Function derivative()
      Determines this function's derivative. It is done in a numerical way using the formula:

      \( f'(x) = \lim\limits_{x \to 0}\dfrac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \)

      That is, the slope of tangent line at a point \( x \) of a function \( y = f(x) \), or: The slope of a line within an infinitely small interval \( [x; x+h] \), where \( h \) is an infinitesimal that approaches \( 0 \). Note that here \( h = 10^{-5} \), which should be accurate enough.
      Returns:
      The derivative by means of \( \frac{dy}{dx} \)

    • derivative

      default Function derivative​(int n)
      Determines the n-th derivative of this function. This function is simply differentiated \( n \) times in an iterative manner until the desired 'count' is reached.
      Parameters:
      n - The number of times to differentiate
      Returns:
      The n-th derivative

    • integral

      default Function integral()
      Determines the integral of this function. It's the area under the curve of a function \( y = f(x) \). It is said that for a function \( y=f(x) \) counts:

      \( \displaystyle\int\limits_{0}^{x_m}f(x)dx = \lim_{h \to 0}\;\;h\displaystyle\sum\limits_{k=0}^{h^{-1}}f(x_k) \)

      It is called the 'Trapezoid Rule'. This approach consists in dissecting the function into infinitely many, infinitely small 'trapezoids' and adding them all up. To improve time complexity, \( h \) is equal to \( 10^{-5} \), which is still a lot, but good enough in most cases. Also, for the sake of simplicity, the formula has been changed to:

      \( \lim\limits_{h \to 0} \;\; \displaystyle\sum\limits_{k=0}^x f(k) \)

      Where the sum is iterated not in steps of \( 1 \), as usual with Gaussian Summations, but in steps of \( h \), as it can be done with a for-loop.
      This function has a time complexity of \( \mathcal{O}(100n) \)
      Returns:
      The indefinite integral

    • integral

      default Function integral​(int n)
      Determines the n-th integral of this function. Note that this method has a big time complexity and it is therefore deprecated to integrate a big number of times:

      \( \mathcal{O}(100x \cdot n) \)

      Where \( x \) is the integral's input and \( n \) is the number of times to integrate the function.
      Parameters:
      n - The number of times to integrate
      Returns:
      The n-th integral

    • integrate

      default double integrate​(double a, double b)
      Integrates this function from 'a' to 'b'. It is equivalent to:

      \( \displaystyle\int\limits_{a}^{b} f(x)dx = F(b)-F(a) \)

      where \( F(x) \) is the integral of this function.
      Parameters:
      a - Lower bound
      b - Upper bound
      Returns:
      The area underneath \( f(x); a \le x \le b \)

    • arcLength

      default double arcLength​(double a, double b)
      Calculates this function's arc's length from 'a' to 'b'. It uses the following formula:

      \( \displaystyle\int\limits_{a}^{b} \sqrt{1+ \left( \frac{dy}{dx} \right)^2}dx \)

      Parameters:
      a - Lower bound
      b - Upper bound
      Returns:
      The arc's length from 'a' to 'b'

    • singleRoot

      default double singleRoot​(int error)
      Calculates a single root of this function. This method uses the Newton-Raphson Method to estimate a root of this function from a random seed. It is said that:
      \( x_{n+1} = x_n - \dfrac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)} \)
      Where \( f(x) \) is the function, \( f'(x) \) is its derivative and \( x_n \) is the guessed root. Therefore, x_{n+1} becomes an always better approximation of the function's root the more often this algorithm is iterated. The initial guess is ideally computed as: new Random.nextDouble() * 7. This guess is computed for as often as the given error value. If that value is exceeded, Double.NaN is returned.
      Parameters:
      error - How often to repeat the algorithm
      Returns:
      An approximation of one single root of this function

    • singleRoot

      default double singleRoot()
      Calculates a single root of this function. This method uses the Newton-Raphson Method to estimate a root of this function from a random seed. It is said that:
      \( x_{n+1} = x_n - \dfrac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)} \)
      Where \( f(x) \) is the function, \( f'(x) \) is its derivative and \( x_n \) is the guessed root. Therefore, \( x_{n+1} \) becomes an always better approximation of the functions root the more often this algorithm is iterated.
      Note that this function simply delegates to singleRoot(100), which should give enough precision in most cases.
      Returns:
      An approximation of one single root of this function

    • polyRoots

      default double[] polyRoots​(int error, int degree)
      Finds all of the roots of this function. This method iteratively invokes singleRoot() (Newton-Raphson algorithm) to ultimately find all of the approximated roots. Let us say that we have a function \( f(x) \) whose roots we will call \( \Omega \). We now perform long-polynomial-division to define another function, \( g(x) \) whose roots are exactly those of \( f(x) \), except for the one root given by singleRoot():
      \( g(x) = \dfrac{f(x) - f(n)}{x - n} \; ; n \in \Omega \)
      Now we repeat this algorithm until \( g(x) \) becomes a degree-0 polynomial, i.e. a constant. Because the original polyRoots() algorithm was designed to find roots of polynomial equations the degree of the polynomial expressed by this function needs to be entered manually.
      Parameters:
      error - Parameter to parse in singleRoot(int error)
      degree - The degree of the polynomial expressed by this function
      Returns:
      An approximation of the zeros of this function

    • polyRoots

      default double[] polyRoots​(int degree)
      Finds all of the roots of this function. This method iteratively invokes singleRoot() (Newton-Raphson algorithm) to ultimately find all of the approximated roots. Let us say that we have a function \( f(x) \) whose roots we will call \( \Omega \). We now perform long-polynomial-division to define another function, \( g(x) \) whose roots are exactly those of \( f(x) \), except for the one root given by singleRoot():
      \( g(x) = \dfrac{f(x) - f(n)}{x - n} \; ; n \in \Omega \)
      Now we repeat this algorithm until \( g(x) \) becomes a degree-0 polynomial, i.e. a constant. Because the original polyRoots() algorithm was designed to find roots of polynomial equations the degree of the polynomial expressed by this function needs to be entered manually. Note that this method simply delegates to polyRoots(100, degree).
      Parameters:
      degree - The degree of the polynomial expressed by this function
      Returns:
      An approximation of the zeros of this function
